# DevCloud Core — OCI Terraform Foundation

DevCloud Core is a modular Terraform (Infrastructure as Code) project that provisions the
foundational Oracle Cloud Infrastructure (OCI) resources for a database development
environment: compartment, networking, gateways, network security groups, and IAM policy.

The design favours **private-by-default networking** — subnets have no public IPs, OCI
service traffic egresses through a Service Gateway, on-prem/peered traffic routes through a
DRG, and internet egress (if enabled) goes through a NAT gateway. It is intended as the base
layer that application servers, databases, and platform services are deployed on top of.

---

## Architecture


tenancy (root)
└── compartment: database-dev
    ├── VCN (10.242.8.0/21, internal DNS enabled)
    │   ├── subnet dbdev-a  10.242.8.0/24   (private)
    │   ├── subnet dbdev-b  10.242.9.0/24   (private)
    │   └── subnet dbdev-c  10.242.10.0/24  (private)
    ├── Route table
    │   ├── OCI services      -> Service Gateway
    │   ├── on-prem / peered  -> DRG
    │   └── 0.0.0.0/0         -> NAT gateway   (optional)
    ├── Service Gateway
    ├── NAT gateway           (optional egress)
    ├── Network Security Groups (+ rules)
    └── IAM policy            (DBA group access)


Subnet CIDRs are **derived** from the VCN CIDR with `cidrsubnet()`, so changing the VCN
range automatically re-carves the subnets.

---

## Modules

| Module           | Purpose                                                        |
| ---------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `compartment`    | Creates the `database-dev` compartment (`enable_delete` on).   |
| `vcn`            | Creates the VCN with internal DNS.                            |
| `subnet`         | Creates private subnets via `for_each` + `cidrsubnet()`.      |
| `routeTable`     | Service Gateway, DRG, and optional NAT routes.               |
| `serviceGateway` | Service Gateway for private OCI service access.              |
| `natGateway`     | Optional NAT gateway for internet egress.                    |
| `nsgList`        | Creates Network Security Groups via `for_each`.             |
| `nsgRules`       | Creates NSG security rules from a single rule map.          |
| `groupPolicy`    | IAM policy granting the DBA group access to the compartment. |

---

## Prerequisites

- [Terraform](https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/downloads) >= 1.5.0
- An OCI tenancy and a user with permission to create the resources above
- The [OCI CLI](https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/API/SDKDocs/cliinstall.htm)
  configured (`oci setup config`) — this project authenticates via the `~/.oci/config`
  profile by default, so **no credentials live in the repo**.

---

## Repository layout


devcloud_core/
├── provider.tf              # provider config (auth via ~/.oci/config profile)
├── versions.tf              # required_version + provider constraint
├── backend.tf               # remote state template (commented)
├── variable.tf              # root input variables
├── main.tf                  # module wiring (dependency order)
├── outputs.tf               # root outputs
├── terraform.tfvars.example # copy -> terraform.tfvars (gitignored)
├── .gitignore
└── module/                  # reusable child modules


---

## Configuration

1. Copy the example variables file and fill in your values (this file is gitignored):


   cp terraform.tfvars.example terraform.tfvars
   

   | Variable         | Required | Description                                          |
   | ---------------- | -------- | ---------------------------------------------------- |
   | `tenancy_ocid`   | yes      | Tenancy OCID (root compartment).                     |
   | `drg_ocid`       | yes      | DRG OCID for on-prem / peered routes.                |
   | `dba_group_ocid` | yes      | IAM group OCID granted compartment access.           |
   | `oci_profile`    | no       | `~/.oci/config` profile name. Default `DEFAULT`.     |
   | `region`         | no       | OCI region. Default `ap-mumbai-1`.                   |

   You can instead export these as environment variables:

   
   export TF_VAR_tenancy_ocid="ocid1.tenancy.oc1..xxxx"
   export TF_VAR_drg_ocid="ocid1.drg.oc1.ap-mumbai-1.xxxx"
   export TF_VAR_dba_group_ocid="ocid1.group.oc1..xxxx"
   

2. (Optional) Enable remote state — see [Remote state](#remote-state).

---

## Usage

# Initialise providers/modules (and the backend, if configured)
terraform init

# Format all files recursively
terraform fmt -recursive

# Validate syntax and internal consistency
terraform validate

# Preview changes; save the plan to a file
terraform plan -out=tfplan

# Apply the saved plan (no re-prompt)
terraform apply tfplan

# Tear everything down
terraform destroy

### Other useful commands

# Inspect outputs (all, one, or as JSON)
terraform output
terraform output subnet_ids
terraform output -json

# Target a single module during development
terraform plan  -target=module.nsgRules
terraform apply -target=module.nsgList

# Refresh/inspect state
terraform state list
terraform state show 'module.vcn.oci_core_vcn.dbdev_vcn'

# Upgrade providers within the version constraint, then lock for all platforms
terraform init -upgrade
terraform providers lock \
  -platform=linux_amd64 -platform=darwin_arm64 -platform=windows_amd64

# Visualise the dependency graph
terraform graph | dot -Tsvg > graph.svg

> After the first `terraform init`, **commit `.terraform.lock.hcl`** — it pins exact
> provider versions/checksums for reproducible builds.

---

## Remote state

State is local by default. For shared/durable state, use OCI Object Storage via the
S3-compatible backend. Uncomment and fill in the block in `backend.tf`, then:

# Create Customer Secret Keys under: Identity > your user > Customer Secret Keys
terraform init \
  -backend-config="access_key=$OCI_S3_ACCESS_KEY" \
  -backend-config="secret_key=$OCI_S3_SECRET_KEY"


Keep the secret key out of the repo (env var or a gitignored `*.auto.tfvars`).

---

## Outputs

| Output                  | Description                              |
| ----------------------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| `compartment_id`        | OCID of the created compartment.         |
| `vcn_id`                | OCID of the VCN.                         |
| `subnet_ids`            | Map of subnet name => OCID.              |
| `nsg_ids`               | Map of NSG name => OCID.                 |
| `route_table_id`        | OCID of the route table.                 |
| `service_gateway_id`    | OCID of the Service Gateway.             |
| `nat_gateway_public_ip` | Public egress IP of the NAT gateway.     |

---

## Security notes

- Authentication is via the `~/.oci/config` profile — no keys, OCIDs, or fingerprints in code.
- `terraform.tfvars`, `*.pem`, `*.auto.tfvars`, and state files are gitignored.
- Subnets are private (`prohibit_public_ip_on_vnic = true`).
- OCI service access is via the Service Gateway; on-prem via the DRG.
- IAM access is scoped to a single group on a single compartment.

> Do **not** commit `terraform.tfvars`, key files, or state. If secrets were ever committed,
> scrub them from git history (e.g. `git filter-repo`) and rotate the affected credentials.

